[2.21 p.m.] ( ) (The Hon. Faiszer Musthapha, PC) Hon. Deputy Chairperson, I consider it a privilege being given the opportunity to speak at the Committee Stage Discussions on the Votes of the Ministry of Public
Administration, Provincial Councils and Local Government and the Ministry of Labour.

As you are aware, provincial councils last had their elections in 2014 and then, their term expired. So, now we are in 2025 and the provinces are without electoral representatives. Fingers have been pointed at various persons. So, I would like to tell this Government that holding the election is a simple process. For the Amendment that was brought in, under which 50 per cent were to be elected under the PR System and 50 per cent under the ward system, two-thirds of the Parliament voted, including the present President. In terms of that process, a Delimitation Commission was appointed by the then President and that Delimitation Commission Report was presented to Parliament by the then Minister; that was me. However, that Commission Report was rejected by every single Member of this House. Then, there was a review committee appointed by the then Speaker, headed by the Prime Minister. At that point of time, the Prime Minister was the Hon. Ranil Wickremesinghe. But, their report was not submitted to the President, and that is the present obstacle to holding the Provincial Council Elections. During President Gotabaya Rajapaksas time, the Prime Minister was the Hon. Mahinda Rajapaksa, followed by the Hon. Ranil Wickremesinghe and subsequently, the Hon. Dinesh Gunawardena. However, the review report on Delimitation Commission Report was not handed over to the President by the Prime Minister in terms of the Act. So, if this House is opposed to the Delimitation Commission Report that was rejected by this House, there is a process through which a review committee could make the relevant changes. Therefore, the present Speaker can appoint a review committee headed by the Prime Minister, and all the grievances in relation to the wards or electorates that were created could be addressed. . , , . , . . . . . , . . , , . 2018 . , .

.. ( .. ) (The Hon. G.G. Ponnambalam) Hon. Presiding Member, I wish to raise three issues very quickly. The first one is this. The suboffices of the local government bodies in the Northern Province have been permited to issue building permits, name change of titles, certificates of compliance, subdivision of lands, amalgamation of lands and street line certificates. But, through a circular, the Northern Provincial Council has informed that, because of lack of capacity, all these six tasks would be handled by the main office of the local government body. That inconveniences the people quite a lot, Hon. Minister. Therefore, I urge you to intervene in this matter and somehow provide all the necessary requirements to ensure that these suboffices are able to carry out these tasks. Otherwise, it will inconvenience the people. Your Governments position is that you must take facilities down to the grassroots, as much as possible. So, if that is the case, then you must intervene in this regard as well.

The other matter, Hon. Minister and Hon. Presiding Member, is that the Chavakachcheri Divisional Secretariat is a quite cumbersome Secretariat. The land area that Divisional Secretariat is supposed to cover is quite enormous. Therefore, there has been a long-time request - I remember, as a Member of Parliament in 2001, I myself making that written request to the Ministry of Public Administration - to somehow divide that Divisional Secretariat into two geographical regions basing Chavakachcheri, as it stands now, and also by creating a new Divisional Secretariat region centering Kodikamam. That must be done.

Finally, Hon. Presiding Member, I would like to refer to a matter which my Colleague who spoke just before me raised regarding the Kalmunai-North Divisional Secretariat. The Kalmunai-North Divisional Secretariat has been recognized since 1989. It was created as an AGA Division and then, by Cabinet Memoranda dated 17/3/1993 and 31/3/1993, the Ministry of Public Administration upgraded it to two Divisional Secretariats and approval was given by Cabinet Memorandum dated 09/07/1993. Since then, Hon. Minister, there have been interferences, unfortunately, due to political reasons, where the Kalmunai-North Divisional Secretariat has not been able to function fully. Literally and systematically, political interference caused it to not have an Accountant and also several parts of the Secretariat unable to function. Several of its current functions are gradually trying to be shifted to the Kalmunai-South Divisional Secretariat. During the previous Government, there was a talk that it was going to be downgraded to a suboffice. That must be stopped, Hon. Minister. That is what your Government came into power for. The decision regarding that Divisional Secretariat was taken in 1989 and it has been in practice. But, due to political interference, the functioning of this Secretariat has been scuttled.
.. ( .. ) (The Hon. G.G. Ponnambalam) I am finishing up, Sir.

I am quite happy to work with the Hon. Member who spoke just before me. I think all the other Hon. Members representing the North and the East, particularly the Eastern Province, will also cooperate. And, we must allow the Kalmunai-North Divisional Secretariat to function fully. It is the right thing to do. It is the only thing you can do, not allow political interference as has been done for several years in the past. I, therefore, urge you very strongly to take immediate action in this regard, and we will give you our fullest cooperation.

I would like to bring to the Hon. Ministers attention that government employees now in service are to get a salary increase in addition to the allowances amounting to Rs. 7,500 being added to the basic salary, as per the Proposal in Budget, 2025. At the same time, a Proposal has also been submitted to revise the pensions of government employees who had retired between 1996 and 31.12.2019, but employees who had retired after 01st Janurary, 2020 and due to retire up to 31st March, 2025 have been overlooked in the Budget, 2025. With the present financial situation in our country and the escalating cost of living, the pensioners who had retired after 01st Janurary, 2020 and due to retire upto 31st March, 2025 are struggling to manage their cost of living and other expenses. Hon. Minister, I would like to request you to consider the letter received from the Oddamavadi Pensioners' Association and I would submit the letter to you. Hon. Minister.
